<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">RCH0007</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:13pt; font-weight:bold">Children’s Services Development Group</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">This briefing set</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s out the views of the Children’s Services Development Group (CSDG) regarding the Government’s planned reforms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> to the regulation of residential children’s homes. It addresses the two questions posed by the Education Select Committee: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Are the DfE’s proposed reforms to the regulation of residential children’s homes appropriate and sufficient?</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.35pt; padding-left:4.65pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Are the reforms likel</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">y to prove effective or further measures are needed?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Children’s Services Development Group (CSDG) welcomes the intention of the proposed reforms to the regulation of children’s homes, but is concerned that the narrow focus of the proposed changes will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> not be effective in ensuring that the system protects vulnerable children and acts in their best interests.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Our concerns stem from both the exclusive focus on out-of-authority placements in children’s homes, which risks ignoring the majority of vulnerabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e children, and from the decision to simply increase regulation when care failings are caused by existing regulations not being followed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">About CSDG</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Children’s Services Development Group is a policy coalition of leading independent providers of spec</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ialist services for looked after children and young people with complex needs. Its members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">‒</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Acorn Care &amp; Education, Hesley Group, National Fostering Agency, Options Group,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Priory Education Services,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> SENAD Group, Witherslack Group and Young</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Foundations </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">–</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">provide services to vulnerable young people, delivering excellent outcomes and value for money across the UK.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q.1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> the DfE’s proposed reforms to the regulation of residential children’s homes appropriate and sufficient</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Children’s Services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Development Group (CSDG) welcomes the intention of the proposed reforms to the regulation of children’s homes, but is concerned that the narrow focus of the proposed changes will not be effective in ensuring that the system protects vulnerable children and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> acts in their best interests.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">All children should have safe, effective care whether in fostering, kinship care or children’s homes, and whether placed in- or out-of-area. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many children at risk will still be living with their birth families, as was the ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">se in Rochdale and in Oxfordshire, and the regulation does nothing to safeguard them.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Rather, it detracts attention from them, and so makes it less likely that abuse will be noticed and acted upon. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">DfE itself recognised that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">existing notification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> process is not always followed, and our concern is that whilst the intentions are good, in practice the changes will not have an impact or could in fact make it worse by delaying children and young people’s access to needed support.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">There is nothing in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">he proposed reforms that makes it more likely that regulations will be implemented effectively. Where the proposed reforms are followed, they have the potential to introduce significant delay to the system. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The involvement of the Director of Children’s S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ervices and the need to consult the area authority should not be allowed to needlessly delay placement decisions being made, whilst the child or young person has to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">remain in a short-term placement and cope with the uncertainty of not knowing where they wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ll be living. Target timescales for the placement decision process should be set out and consideration should be given to the impact a temporary placement will have or be having whilst decisions are being made.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Below we set out our response to specific parts of the proposed reforms: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Risk assessments</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSDG would welcome clear guidance on what should be included in risk assessments, which is currently lacking. CSDG members have recently trialled risk assessments </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">and have been met with very varied responses from police services and local authorities. There needs to be requirements on all parties to co-operate, not just children’s homes, for this to be effective. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Ongoing communication between agencies, not just at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> the beginning of a placement or at annual reviews, is essential. Where one party becomes aware of a risk in a local area this should be communicated to all as it arises and acted upon to safeguard all vulnerable children in the area, not just those in chi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ldren’s homes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where homes are inadequate or located in unsafe areas, this must be addressed and quickly, but the majority of children’s homes provide young people with intensive and specialist therapeutic support that will enable them to live fulfilled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">adult lives. The DfE’s own data shows that 71% of children’s homes are rated good or outstanding, and there is no direct correlation between level of deprivation and location of children’s homes. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Where local authorities lack provision, and so turn to out-o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f-area placements, we would encourage them to work in partnership with providers to develop high quality provision that meets children’s needs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Distance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The focus on out-of-area placements ignores the risks to all vulnerable and looked-after children, many of whom will already have a history of neglect or abuse before entering care. All placement decisions should be carefully planned and considered, in par</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">tnership between local authorities, providers and other agencies, in order to support children in safe and therapeutic environments to achieve good outcomes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The most important consideration is that a placement meets the needs of a child and is in their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">best interests. Distance is just one factor in this. Indeed, it can be necessary to use out-of-area placements in order to access specialist provision – especially </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">for looked-after children with special educational needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> – or to remove a young people from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">harmful environment for their own protection and wellbeing.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Placement decisions must be in the best interests of the child, and not based on short-term costs. Research by the LGiU shows that 86% of local authorities say that achieving excellent outcomes i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s their priority in commissioning, but for 40% or more of all placement decisions, cost is their primary concern.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Distance in itself need not have a negative impact as long as good contact and communication between agencies is well maintained. Some local</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> authorities do not establish this communication and multi-agency approach for children in-authority and the focus on out-of-area placements risks ignoring the needs of all vulnerable children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">In determining whether there is a ‘correct’ level of out-of-a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">rea placements, it is necessary to look at the reasons why each child is being placed out-of-area and the provision they are accessing. Where shortages in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">exist, local authorities should look to work with providers to develop services that, in tim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">e, will meet the needs of the local population</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, using demographic data to plan for the future</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Care leavers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The presumption should always be that young people will leave care later than age</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">17, and any decisions for a young person to leave before that s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hould be exceptional circumstances. Local authorities, working in partnership with providers, should regularly review the type of support young people are receiving and how this meets their current needs and prepares them for independent adult life. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Leav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ing care is too often treated as an event, not a process. Planning for care leaving should start early and the intensity of support phased to help young people adjust to increasing levels of independence. This would help ensure corporate parents mirror the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> kind of support offered by birth families, and would improve outcomes in education, training and employment for looked-after children.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Raising the care leaving age would be more effective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> than simply requiring sign off</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. Decisions about care leaving are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">still too often driven by short-term cost factor and not long-term outcomes for young people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Workforce</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSDG broadly welcomes the proposals to increase the quality and level of qualifications of the care workforce. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">It is important that all looked-after c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">hildren have access to high quality care, and qualified staff is one of the key factors in achieving this. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">However, up-skilling the workforce will require significant resource investment and it is not clear whether Government, provider or the individual</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> will be asked to meet the cost of training. In addition to this, better qualified staff will attract higher salaries, which may have a knock on impact on the cost of provision and must be incorporated into local authorities’ commissioning. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Recent c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">omment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Education Secretary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Michael Gove</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSDG were very disappointed to read the Education Secretary’s recent article in the Daily Telegraph, which was misleading and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> harmfully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> sensationalist.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> In a number of instances data</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">from the DfE’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s Homes D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ata </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> was,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> willfully or mistakenly,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> misrepresented</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The DfE’s own data shows that 71% of children’s homes are rated good or outstanding, and there is no direct correlation between level of deprivation and location of children’s homes.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Quality is not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> a question of whether the provider a local authority or independent provider. Indeed, independent homes were less likely to be rated inadequate, and cost on average over £14,000 less per child per year, than local authority-run homes. Quality is a questio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">n of whether a placement meets the often complex needs of a vulnerable child in a safe and fulfilling environment. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Q.2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are the reforms</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> likely to prove effective</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> or further measures are needed?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSDG welcome the intentions of these changes to i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">mprove multi-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">agency working and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> communication. However, current problems in the system are often caused by poor implementation and so changing regulations may not have much impact without also looking at the way local authorities commission services and communicate wit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">h providers and other agencies. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Revising regulations without acting to ensure effective implementation and better strategic commissioning of placements will not truly make a difference in the lives of children in the care system. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Better commissioning a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd collaborative, constructive relationships with providers are needed to ensure that placements work to support, encourage and safeguard looked-after children in their care, as well as to develop the right kind of provision locally to meet their needs. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><br /><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without this foundation of better commissioning and a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">positive attitude to partnership working, the regulations will not be effective and in some local authorities, short-term costs, not the value of long-term outcomes, will continue to drive decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Without a wider strategic approach to the care system, the Department for Education is simply tinkering with isolated parts of the s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ystem – such as the adoption reforms – which will mean nothing for the majority of children in care. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Specifically the way children’s homes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">are used in the care system needs to be reviewed. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The Department for Education has recognised that too often children’s homes are used by local authorities as a ‘last resort’. 7,900 of the 67,000 looked-after children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">in England are cared for in residential homes,</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">CSDG</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> believe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> that residential care can and should play a vital role as part of a range of provision for children with complex needs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Many young people in residential homes will have had multiple placeme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nt breakdowns and often have the most complex needs. Statistics released in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Children’s Homes Data Pack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> show that nearly a third of children in children’s homes have had 6 or more placements.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> This is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">the real</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> scandal, with poor commissioning denying ch</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">ildren stable and secure placements that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> meet their needs, and robbing them of positive outcomes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Recent parliamentary questions have revealed that the Department for Education decided against developing a care strategy.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Instead the department has chosen to implement piecemeal reforms – such as to the adoption system – which makes no difference to the majority of looked-after children. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">We would encourage the Education Select Committee to ask the Government to rethink th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">is decision as a matter of urgency and take a strategic approach to reforming the wider care system, rather than making piecemeal changes in isolation. Only by doing so will they safeguard vulnerable children and help to provide the high-quality care and s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">upport they deserve.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.csdg.org.uk/images/pdfs/In%20It%20Together%20In%20Practice%20-%20CSDG%20and%20LGiU%20report%202012.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.csdg.org.uk/images/pdfs/In%20It%20Together%20I</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">n%20Practice%20-%20CSDG%20and%20LGiU%20report%202012.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/children_shealth/10304696/Michael-Gove-Im-ending-this-scandal-over-childrens-care.html"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/children_shealth/10304696</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">/Michael-Gove-Im-ending-this-scandal-over-childrens-care.html</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/c/childrens%20homes%20data%20pack%202013.PDF"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://media.education.gov.uk/assets/files/pdf/c/childrens%20homes%20data%20pack%202</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">013.PDF</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; fo